[1] Cholera - Burundi
Date: Fri 29 Oct 2004
From: Pablo Nart <pablo11@hotpop.com>
Source: IOL.co.za [edited]
<http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=68&art_id=qw1099048141583B653>

Cholera outbreak grips Burundi
-------------------------------
A cholera epidemic has struck the town of Rumonge in the central African
state of Burundi, with at least 140 cases and a death reported since
mid-October 2004, a local council official said on Fri 29 Oct 2004.
Emile Hicintuka, an administrative official of the town, about 100 km south
of the capital, Bujumbura said: "Yesterday [Thu 28 Oct 2004], 20 people
were hospitalized, compared to 40 the day before."
Cholera was endemic in the town due to "lack of drinking water and poor
hygiene typical of Rumonge," said local health care chief Dr. Gloriose
Nahimana. "The arrival of the rainy season every year worsens the
situation, and this time the problem has become particularly acute," she
warned.
Hicintuka said 20 cases had been admitted to Rumonge hospital on Thu 28 Oct
2004, bringing the total to 140 since the outbreak began on 12 Oct 2004.
"We've had confirmation for 5 days now that it's a cholera outbreak,
because we've had analyses done in Bujumbura," he said. Despite its size,
about 50 000 inhabitants, Rumonge did not have suitable laboratory
facilities, the official admitted.
"Several non-governmental organizations are on hand to help out," he
explained: "They are distributing drinking water, disinfecting houses and
unsanitary premises, and providing instruction in hygiene."
--
Pablo Nart
<pablo11@hotpop.com>
