[2] Cholera - Uganda
Date: Fri 29 Oct 2004
From: Pablo Nart <pablo11@hotpop.com>
Source: Borneo Bulletin [edited]
<http://www.brunet.bn/news/bb/fri/oct29w26.htm>

Cholera outbreak in Ugandan camp, 2 dead
-------------------------------------------
Aid workers said that the disease, which broke out in Pabbo camp, 400 km
north of the Ugandan capital Kampala, was caused by poor sanitary
conditions, including a lack of pit latrines, for the 62 000 war-displaced
people living in the camp.
50 people, including 9 children and 17 women, were infected when the
disease broke out. 2 men died, 39 people recovered, and 9 were still being
treated, according to Elianne Duthoit, the head of the UN Humanitarian
Coordination office in Kampala.
"A number of relief agencies moved in to contain the situation. We are
embarking on building more latrines in the camp, providing jerry cans, and
community health workers are sensitizing the population, telling them the
advantages of using chlorinated water," Duthoit said by telephone on Thu 28
Oct 2004.
"We had 50 cases since the outbreak. The cause is poor sanitation. There
were not enough latrines. Now there is a coordination group which meets
regularly to review the situation," she said.
--
