[3] Cholera - Senegal
Date: Wed 27 Oct 2004
From: Pablo Nart <pablo11@hotpop.com>
Source: IOL.co.za [edited]
<http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=68&art_id=qw1098898203880B252>

The number of people infected in an outbreak of cholera in the Dakar region
of Senegal has risen to 126, the committee charged with monitoring the
spread of the disease said on Wed 27 Oct 2004.
On Tue 26 Oct 2004, the health ministry said 84 cases had been recorded, 2
of which had been fatal, since the 1st patients were identified on 11 Oct 2004.
"Up until today [Wed 27 Oct 2004], we have counted 126 declared cases of
cholera nationwide," according to Professor Papa Salif Sow, head of the
infectious diseases service at Dakar's Fann hospital and committee coordinator.
The outbreak is the 1st reappearance of cholera in the West African state
of Senegal since 1997. Medical sources say the last epidemic took place in
1995 to 1996. The 1st cases in the current outbreak were recorded in the
working class district of Colobane in central Dakar. Cases were later found
throughout the capital and its suburbs.
2 suspected cases have been identified at Rufisque, about 30 km from Dakar,
a senior health ministry official told reporters, but none in the country's
hinterland. Health professionals remain on alert, and clinics are
continuing to receive the medical supplies needed to contain the outbreak.
In schools and colleges, hygiene lessons have been introduced, and the
street sale of plastic bags of water, and of fruit and vegetables, in Dakar
has been banned.
"We have launched disinfection campaigns in houses in which sick people
live, and around stagnant water, to prevent them becoming reservoirs for
bacteria," Sow said.
--
